      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. i'm not sure if i can use valgrind on this specific hardware since it's a resource-constrained microcontroller. what are some other ways to track this down using just the code and standard logging?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Valgrind might be a bit too heavyweight for a resource-constrained microcontroller. In that case, you can try using some standard logging techniques to track down the memory leak. One approach is to use a \"leak detector\" class that keeps track of the memory allocations and deallocations in your code. This class can be like a little watchdog, constantly checking if any memory is being allocated but not freed.\n\nFor example, you could create a class that inherits from `std::unique_ptr` and overrides the `reset` method to log a message whenever an object is deallocated. This way, you can see which objects are being released and which ones are still hanging around.\n\nAnother approach is to use a simple logging mechanism that prints out the memory addresses of all objects that are being allocated and deallocated. This can be like shouting out \"Hey, I'm being allocated!\" or \"Hey, I'm being freed!\" to help you track down the leak.\n\nYou can also try using a memory tracking library like Newriva's Memory Tracker, which is specifically designed for resource-constrained microcontrollers. It's like having a tiny, resource-efficient team of memory detectives, searching through the code and reporting back to you.\n\nAnd, of course",
      "source": "target",
